rg:80/person/A44219C0-A25E-43F7-9F6B-3342A0195BED"><gtr:id>A44219C0-A25E-43F7-9F6B-3342A0195BED</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Jung Jin</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Park</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE005268%2F1"><gtr:id>A910D846-B650-4A3A-9B93-562D963DA4AA</gtr:id><gtr:title>Exploring public acceptance of modern technology development in protected areas</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E005268/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research aims to enhance understanding of: the significance of the protected landscapes in a post-industrial society; and the changing relationships between people and landscapes. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The award builds on PhD research which was undertaken on mobile telecommunications development in the Peak District National Park. The PhD research found that: there is a high level of sensitivity to minor and incremental landscape change in the relatively natural landscapes of areas protected by National Park designation; and that even in a post-industrial society the public are not solely driven by technological convenience. The Government?s environmental policies and land use planning rules are inadequate to capture the intrinsic landscape value of the National Park as it is appreciated by the general public and the conservation sector. The research also provides justification for public participation in decision making processes by identifying people?s values as underlying factors significantly affecting their attitudes towards changing landscapes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>By widely disseminating this knowledge to key stakeholders and the general public, this research will have positive effects on policy making and implementation and landscape planning and management for sustainable land use. The award holder is continuing investigation into development conflicts in protected landscapes.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-02-29</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>58589</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>C65F4281-EA73-481D-A801-0FCF5A8F067F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Perceived landscape impacts of mobile telecommunications development in the Peak District National Park, England</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Environmental Planning and Management</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9aee1ee63386515068fab667d68cc059"><gtr:id>9aee1ee63386515068fab667d68cc059</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Park J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cf9af9adbbb959</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>ED3BA308-7AE3-4B61-9C8F-61EC726A2811</gtr:id><gtr:title>Balancing landscape and development: A case study of mobile telecommunications development in the Peak District National Park, England</gtr:title><gtr